  1. These data are specific to one week and therefore may not be indicative of overall hapiness levels for the individuals. They could easily be influenced by random outside factors. If we assume they are representative samples, though, we can analyse differences in happiness levels.
alex<-c(4,3.5,5,4.5,2,5,5)
shannon<-c(2.5,3,4.5,3,1,4.5,5)
hist(alex)

hist(shannon)

mean(alex)-mean(shannon)
## [1] 0.7857143

Clearly, the data are not normal - they are skewed and not unimodal. The data are very small. To do a test, though, lets assume that the data are representative - after all they were collected from a random week. H0: mu(alex)=mu(shannon) Ha: mu(alex)=mu(shannon) There is an observed difference in the means of the collected samples: alexs mean is 0.7857143 higher than shannons. Lets do a matched pairs permutation to see if this difference is significant.

alex<-c(4,3.5,5,4.5,2,5,5)
shannon<-c(2.5,3,4.5,3,1,4.5,5)

diff <- alex - shannon
actual.test.stat <- mean(diff)

test.stat.diff <- NULL
set.seed(311)
for(i in 1:100000){
  sign <- sample(c(-1,1), size = length(diff), replace = TRUE)
  random.diff <- diff*sign
  test.stat.diff[i] <- mean(random.diff)
}
#Let's look at our null distribution
hist(test.stat.diff)

#Calculate p-value
mean(test.stat.diff >= actual.test.stat) *2
## [1] 0.0323

Using a matched-pairs permutation test, we determine that the p value is significant, at 0.03126. There are issues with this procedure, though. While this week is a random sample, one individual week out of 56 is likely not indicative of overall happiness. Ranking happiness with numbers is also likely not a perfect representation of feelings. When were the data collected during the day? There are too many questions to state a conclusion. Within the observed data, alexs recorded happiness is greater than shannons, and the test run without context would state that alex is more happy than shannon, but the data is quite small.

tab <- matrix(c('-100 (type I)', '200 (power)', '50', '-50 (type II)'), ncol=2, byrow=TRUE)

Based on our outcome table, we want to be correct to maximize our emotional value. So when can we be sure with the least amount of rolls? Means:

So we can see that the biased die would have a mean of 6, significantly higher than 4.5. We are trying to figure out n. We may have to try ranges of alpha and n values. Lets find standard deviations

#fair die

Let our null hypothesis be that the die is fair (innocent until proven guilty). Then our null distribution has mean 4.5 and standard deviation sqrt(21). Using an alpha value of 0.01, to minimize the chance of a -100 value and increase likelihood of a +50 outcome (.99 if the die is fair) we can plot many different probabilities of a type II error and power. Based on our hypotheses, the power correlates to a correct accusation of cheating (+200) whereas 1-power = P(type II error) correlates to -50 points. We also must factor in -1 for every die rolled.

x<-1:100
ans<-NULL
for(i in 1:length(x)){
  n<-i
  distance<-4.5-qnorm(0.005, 4.5, sqrt(21)/sqrt(n))
  power<-pnorm(4.5-distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(n)) + pnorm(4+distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(n), lower.tail = FALSE)
  ans[i]<-200*power -n -50*(1-power) #what we want to maximize
}
plot(x,ans)

which.max(ans)
## [1] 80

For an alpha value of 0.01, the we have a maximum at 80 rolls. Lets try different alpha values. We will run a nested for loop checking different alpha values as well as the different number of rolls above. We also change our emotional change expression to represent all four outcomes.

alpha_vals<-1-.01*seq(from=80, to=99.99, by=0.01)
x<-1:100
maxes<-NULL
for(i in 1:length(alpha_vals)){
  ans<-NULL
  for(j in 1:length(x)){
    distance<-4.5-qnorm(alpha_vals[i], 4.5, sqrt(21)/sqrt(j))
    power<-pnorm(4.5-distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(j)) + pnorm(4+distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(j), lower.tail = FALSE)
    ans[j]<-200*power -j -50*(1-power) -100*(alpha_vals[i]) + 50*(1-alpha_vals[i]) #what we want to maximize - different from before as we are factoring type one errors.
  }
  maxes[i]<-max(ans)
}
which.max(maxes)
## [1] 829
alpha_vals[829]
## [1] 0.1172

This says that the 829th value contains the maximum. Lets run our maximizing function for the corresponding alpha=0.1172

x<-1:100
ans<-NULL
for(i in 1:length(x)){
  n<-i
  distance<-4.5-qnorm(0.0586, 4.5, sqrt(21)/sqrt(n))
  power<-pnorm(4.5-distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(n)) + pnorm(4+distance,6,sqrt(21)/sqrt(n), lower.tail = FALSE)
  ans[i]<-200*power -n -50*(1-power) #what we want to maximize
}
plot(x,ans)

max(ans)
## [1] 133.9341
which.max(ans)
## [1] 49

This shows that to maximize the emotional change, we should use an alpha value of 0.1172 and roll 49 times. This would give us an expected emotional change of +133.9341. So we should roll 49 times.

  1. The poisson distributions population variance is modeled by mu, the same as the mean. The bootstrap t confidence interval should to a better job almost always than the bootrap percentile interval. For small samples, the bootstrap percentile interval is often too narrow, but starts to handle skewness well for larger n. However, the bootstrap t is the best interval for almost all n, and handles skewness better than all other intervals. The coverage rates for the bootstrap t confidence interval will be proximate to the desired confidence level for almost all n, with a small error for small n. Alternatively the bootstrap percentile interval has a relatively low coverage rate for small n and slowly converges towards the desired confidence level. Sampling poisson variances for large n sees the variances emulate the cdf of the poisson distribution, same for the pdf. This means that the pdf of the estimation for population variance will be unimodal and somewhat symmetrical, although the poisson distribution will provide some skew. This means the bootstrap t-confidence interval will be superior to the bootstrap percentile interval for small and medium n, but they will be mostly the same for large n as they both converge to the desired confidence level. To test this, lets use a poisson(10) distribution.
#Boot for pop variance of poisson(10)
boot_confidence<-NULL
lambda<-10
#change confidence level and n
confidence_level<-.90
confidence_tail<-(1-confidence_level)/2
n<-10
for(i in 1:10000){
  pois_dist<-rpois(n,lambda)
  boot<-sample(pois_dist, size=n, replace=TRUE)
  
  boot_low_bound<-quantile(boot, confidence_tail)
  boot_up_bound<-quantile(boot, confidence_tail+confidence_level)
  if(var(pois_dist)>boot_low_bound){
    if(var(pois_dist)<boot_up_bound){
      boot_confidence[i]<-TRUE
    } else{
      boot_confidence[i]<-FALSE
    }
  } else{
    boot_confidence[i]<-FALSE
  }
}
boot_coverage_rate<-mean(boot_confidence)
boot_coverage_rate
## [1] 0.5513
#boot t- for pop variance of poisson(10)
boot_t_confidence<-NULL
lambda<-10
ans<-NULL
#change confidence level and n
confidence_level<-.90
confidence_tail<-(1-confidence_level)/2
n<-10
for(i in 1:10000){
  pois_dist<-rpois(n,lambda)
  boot<-sample(pois_dist, size=n, replace=TRUE)
  
  #boot-t
  ans[i] <- (var(boot)-lambda)/(sd(boot)/sqrt(n))
  x_bar <- var(boot)#as mean and var are same for poisson
  boott_low_bound<- var(boot) - quantile(ans, confidence_level+confidence_tail)*sd(boot)/sqrt(n)
  boott_up_bound<- var(boot) - quantile(ans, confidence_tail)*sd(boot)/sqrt(n)

  if(lambda>boott_low_bound){
    if(lambda<boott_up_bound){
      boot_t_confidence[i]<-TRUE
    } else{
      boot_t_confidence[i]<-FALSE
    }
  } else{
    boot_t_confidence[i]<-FALSE
  }
}
boott_coverage_rate<-mean(boot_t_confidence)
boott_coverage_rate
## [1] 0.8972

The above code shows how inaccurate bootstrapping is for small n, whereas the bootstrap t is very close. The bootstrap coverage is only 55% whereas the bootstrap t coverage is almost exactly our desired confidence leve of 90%. Then as n increases,

  1. We are looking at a graph displaying plots of 19 (x,y) coordinates with Average team sprint distance in meters on the x-axis, and average team number of sprints on the y-axis. The graph displays the average team sprint distance on the x axis and the number of sprints on the y axis. All but one team are farily linearly correlated in the positive x and y directions. Leeds is a significant outlier, close to double the next highest team in both the x and y values. This outlier may position the reader to imagine a stronger correlation. It also skews the axes, again making a correlation look stronger, whereas if we zoomed into the non-outlier points, a correlation may seem weaker.

distance<-c(1480, 1490, 1489, 1505, 1560, 1570, 1595, 1579, 1600, 1605, 1650, 1700, 1715, 1715, 1755, 1760, 1765, 1790, 2360)

.0552*2000-5.2624
## [1] 105.1376

we would expect about 105 sprints. The residuals are certainly distributed with a mean of 0, but their variance is a bit off.   1. To find a confidence interval, lets bootstrap. We need to remove the outlier as we are permuting rows and the outlier would significantly alter the rest of the data. We already know that the removal of the outlier doesnt change the predicted line.
distance<-c(1480, 1490, 1489, 1505, 1560, 1570, 1595, 1579, 1600, 1605, 1650, 1700, 1715, 1715, 1755, 1760, 1765, 1790)
number<-c(72,78,81,85,77,82,81,79,83,80,87,84,87,95,95,93,92,93)
sprints<-data.frame(distance, number)
ans<-NULL
n<-nrow((sprints))
set.seed(310)
for(i in 1:10000){
  index <- sample(n, replace = TRUE)
  new<-sprints[index,]
  new_model<-lm(number ~ distance, data = new)
  ans[i]<-new_model$coefficients[[2]]
}

quantile(ans,c(0.025, .975))
##       2.5%      97.5% 
## 0.03822063 0.07224524

A confidence interval built in this way will contain the true slope, or increase in the average number of sprints for each additional meter increase in the average team sprint distance, 95% of the time. This confidence interval either does or does not contain the true average. Based on our collected data and model, though, it does. So our 95% interval estimate for the slope (increase in average number of sprints for each individual meter increase in the average sprint distance) is (0.03874092, 0.07261936).
